{
  "texts": [
    "These two approaches correspond to the measurement of subjective and objective aspects of fairness, respectively.",
    "The former captures people's feelings and perceptions of the fairness of an event, while the latter focuses on the inherent fairness of the event itself.",
    "This theoretical framework lays the groundwork for measuring perceptions of fairness.",
    "By considering the dimensions of justice and integrating the concepts of informational and interpersonal justice, researchers can effectively assess how individuals perceive fairness in various contexts and enhance our understanding of the multifaceted nature of fairness perception.",
    "In the realm of higher education, colleges, and universities can be seen as microcosms of society, while individual classes in which students are enrolled can be likened to organizations."
  ]
}